Perfect! I can now see the issue clearly. In the `setMatch` function:

1. It gets the host from the request (which includes the port)
2. It tries to find matches using the regexp directly on the full host

The problem is that when a route has `wildcardHostPort = true`, the `Match` method (line 177-182) strips the port before checking:
```go
if r.wildcardHostPort {
    // Don't be strict on the port match
    if i := strings.Index(host, ":"); i != -1 {
        host = host[:i]
    }
}
```

But the `setMatch` method doesn't do the same stripping. So when it tries to extract variables from the full host `test.localhost:8080` using a regex pattern that expects `test.localhost`, it fails.

The fix is to apply the same port-stripping logic in `setMatch` when extracting variables.

